    {
        "content": "<p>Hello, I am looking for a way to tensor product to linear functionals.</p>\n<p>Basically, if I have Module k H and linear functions a, b : H -&gt; k, I want to get the tensor product a \\otimes b : H \\otimes H -&gt; k.</p>\n<p>When I try to do this, I instead get H \\otimes H -&gt; k \\otimes k. I am trying to see if I can replace k \\otimes k with k (as they are equivalent) but have been unable to do so. I was wondering if anyone knows of any easy way to get  a \\otimes b : H \\otimes H -&gt; k?</p>",
        "id": 467999315,
        "sender_full_name": "Lev Stambler",
        "timestamp": 1725576774
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>you could just compose with <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=LinearMap.mul%27#doc\">docs#LinearMap.mul'</a></p>",
        "id": 468005927,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1725579465
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thank you <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"243562\">@Adam Topaz</span> </p>\n<p>Do you have any recommendations as to how to find these different statements across Mathlib or is it something that just comes with time and familiarity?</p>",
        "id": 468201127,
        "sender_full_name": "Lev Stambler",
        "timestamp": 1725632475
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In this case, I found it using the following code:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n\n<span class=\"kd\">noncomputable</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kn\">section</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">TensorProduct</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">in</span>\n<span class=\"kd\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">k</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Field</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">k</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">k</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⊗</span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">k</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">k</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→ₗ</span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">k</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">k</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">exact</span><span class=\"bp\">?%</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 468202847,
        "sender_full_name": "Adam Topaz",
        "timestamp": 1725632984
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Okay sure. Does <code> exact?%</code> look for a type completion?</p>",
